## Ports and Adapters

### Driving (Primary) Ports — how the application is used
Interfaces defined by the application that the outside world calls:

```java
// Port (interface — part of application core)
public interface PlaceOrderUseCase {
    OrderId placeOrder(PlaceOrderCommand command);
}

// Adapter (implementation — lives in infrastructure)
@RestController
public class OrderController {
    private final PlaceOrderUseCase placeOrderUseCase; // depends on interface

    @PostMapping("/orders")
    public ResponseEntity<OrderResponse> placeOrder(@RequestBody OrderRequest req) {
        OrderId id = placeOrderUseCase.placeOrder(new PlaceOrderCommand(req));
        return ResponseEntity.ok(new OrderResponse(id));
    }
}
```

### Driven (Secondary) Ports — what the application depends on
Interfaces defined by the application for its outgoing dependencies:

```java
// Port (interface — part of application core)
public interface OrderRepository {
    void save(Order order);
    Optional<Order> findById(OrderId id);
}

// Adapter (implementation — infrastructure)
@Repository
public class JpaOrderRepository implements OrderRepository {
    // Spring Data JPA implementation
}
```

## Benefits and Trade-offs

### Benefits:
- **Testability** — domain logic tested with no Spring context (fast unit tests)
- **Replaceability** — swap JPA for MongoDB by writing a new adapter
- **Framework independence** — business rules survive framework upgrades
- **Clarity** — explicit what goes in/out of the application

### Trade-offs:
- **More classes** — interfaces + implementations + mappers per concept
- **Mapping overhead** — convert between domain model and JPA entity
- **Learning curve** — team must understand the pattern

```java
// Fast unit test — no Spring, no DB, no network
@Test
void shouldCalculateOrderTotal() {
    var repo = mock(OrderRepository.class);
    var service = new OrderService(repo); // inject mock

    var order = service.placeOrder(new PlaceOrderCommand(...));

    assertThat(order.getTotal()).isEqualTo(Money.of(150, USD));
}
// Runs in milliseconds
```
